Imagine a very long Web page with many sections (e.g., specifications on a single HTML page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), what would happen if the web server first streamed this section, then the others?
Stream order:
1. beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure that sections 1 to 6 are inserted *above* section 7 on the web page.
Does that seem clear to you? Could that be useful?
What I want to achieve is to have the rendering of the linked section (#section7) as fast as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want to have a very long HTML document, but with the rendering of the linked sections as fast as possible. It should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would be streamed out of order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it were streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize documents like that even without JS. You can't use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to tell the server which section you want to see first. To reorganize the parts, you have the following options:
1. Use cascading style sheets
2. Use a template with placeholders
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) doesn't match the DOM order. It could be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and then the browser would reorganize the DOM content into the correct order.
But the approach with positions seems promising. I'll try it.
@user22 oh, you want the browser to fix the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first only to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. It would be good if it could do this without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make sure that the final result (DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
